[The initial detection of SBV, a teratogenic orthobunyavirus in ruminants, as a novel entity led the 1st infected countries (2011, 2012) to report it to the OIE as an "emerging disease". The definition of such a disease, according to OIE's Terrestrial Animal Health Code, is "a new infection or infestation resulting from the evolution or change of an existing pathogenic agent, a known infection or infestation spreading to a new geographic area or population, or a previously unrecognized pathogenic agent or disease diagnosed for the 1st time and which has a significant impact on animal or public health". In May 2012, the said 9 countries (Belgium, Netherlands, Germany, France, UK, Luxembourg, Spain, Italy and Switzerland) discontinued their reporting of SBV to the OIE, declaring that they did not regard the virus, which got widely disseminated within their respective territories, as "emerging" anymore, and since SBV is not listed by the OIE among its reportable diseases. Since then, the virus has been reported from at least 14 additional countries, but no immediate notifications about that have been submitted to the OIE. Some of these counties included information in their annual reports. The additional countries are: Czech Republic, Ireland, Norway, Slovenia, Finland, Denmark, Sweden, Estonia, Austria, Hungary, Poland, Russia, Serbia and Kazakhstan. Romania's situation is, at present, unclear; initially it was suspected to be infected (based upon serological evidence in cattle), but the serological results are to be rechecked.

It will be interesting to obtain information on the laboratory evidence for the claimed SBV infection in Azerbaijan as well as about possible clinical observations there. In February 2012, the Azerbaijani News source ABC.AZ wrote:
"Azerbaijan, which is importing actively breeding stock from countries hit by the new virus [SBV], has neither imposed any restrictions nor announced toughening of border veterinary control. As a result, one cannot rule out that Schmallenberg has been already on the territory of Azerbaijan. (http://abc.az/eng/news/61905.html)

Azerbaijan's cattle population is 2 681 866 (OIE's 2012 data).

SBV has also been suspected in Turkey, based upon serology (see ProMED-mail post 20130510.1704469); a request for additional information or confirmation from another laboratory is pending.

The possible presence of SBV in South Africa has been put to discussion in a recent paper:
Leask, R., Botha, A.M. & Bath, G.F., 2013, 'Schmallenberg virus -- Is it present in South Africa?', Journal of the South African Veterinary Association 84(1), Art. #535, 4 pages. http://dx.doi.org/10.4102/jsava.v84i1.535.

The international status of SBV, probably including its reporting requirements and certification for international trade in animals and their products, is expected to be addressed by an OIE experts forum in September 2013. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Azerbaijan can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/21Bi.]

******
[2] Poland, wildlife
Date: Fri 16 Aug 2013 [accessed on 22 Aug 2013]
Source: The Veterinary Journal, available online 16 Aug 2013 [edited]
http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1090023313003882


First detection of Schmallenberg virus in elk (Alces alces) indicating infection of wildlife in Bia owie a National Park in Poland
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Abstract
--------
Schmallenberg virus (SBV) RNA was detected in the serum of an elk (_Alces alces_) calf captured on the outskirts of Bialowieza National Park (BNP) in December 2012, and shortly afterwards the calf died of acute bronchopneumonia. Serum samples from 169 animals, including bison, red and fallow deer, originating from 8 locations situated in 4 Polish Provinces, were tested for the presence of SBV-specific antibodies between 2011 and 2013. Although no antibodies were found in samples collected up to July 2012, positive samples subsequently appeared between November 2012 and January 2013 in all of the sampled regions. The introduction of SBV infection to the European bison (_Bison bonasus_) population of BNP between July and November 2012 was also confirmed.

--
Communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview English Longhorns
Gut Laach
